{"title_page": "Caroline Tolbert", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Caroline Tolbert\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Colorado College]]|[[Kent State University]]|[[University of Iowa]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[University of California, Santa Barbara]]|[[University of Colorado, Boulder]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Collegiate Scholar Award, University of Iowa}}\n}}\n'''Caroline Tolbert''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]]. She is a professor of political science at the [[University of Iowa]]. She studies [[elections]], [[voting]], and [[civic engagement]] in American politics. Much of her work deals with peoples' capacity to use internet technology, digital technology policy, and the relationship between technology use and social participation.\n\n==Early work and education==\nTolbert attended the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]], graduating with a BA in political science in 1989.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://clas.uiowa.edu/polisci/people/caroline-j-tolbert |title=\nCaroline J. Tolbert |publisher=University of Iowa |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> She then received an MA in [[public policy]] from the [[University of Colorado, Boulder]] in 1991,<ref name=profile/> followed by a PhD in political science from the same institution in 1996.<ref name=kim19>{{cite journal |title=The Political Science 400: With Citation Counts by Cohort, Gender, and Subfield |doi=10.1017/S1049096518001786 |date=April 2019 |last1=Kim |first1=Hannah June |last2=Grofman |first2=Bernard |journal=PS: Political Science & Politics |volume=52 |issue=2 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/C1EDBF7220760F01A5C4A685DB3B3F44/S1049096518001786a.pdf/political_science_400_with_citation_counts_by_cohort_gender_and_subfield.pdf |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 1997, Tolbert was an information technology specialist at [[Colorado College]], and then joined the political science faculty at [[Kent State University]] in 1997.<ref name=profile/> In 2006 she moved to the University of Iowa.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nTolbert has been a coauthor of 8 books.<ref name=profile/> In 2013 she coauthored the book ''Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity'' with [[Karen Mossberger]] and William W. Franko. The book develops a notion of \"digital citizenship\", which captures the extent to which individuals are capable of regularly and effectively using technology related to the internet.<ref name=lseblog>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2013/03/19/book-review-digital-cities-the-internet-and-the-geography-of-opportunity/ |title=Book Review: Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity by [[Karen Mossberger]] et al |date=19 March 2013 |publisher=London School of Economics |last=Spicer |first=Zachary |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The authors focus on inequality in peoples' capacities to use internet technologies; Zachary Spicer, in a review of the book, wrote that they demonstrate that \"America is falling short in these areas and, as a result, information inequities are developing that could have deep and lasting impacts on the social fabric of the country.\"<ref name=lseblog/> The book also presents policy suggestions for making digital citizenship more equal.<ref name=lseblog/>\n\nTolbert became a coauthor of the American politics textbook ''We the people: An introduction to American politics'' when the book was in its ninth edition in 2012.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/We-People-Introduction-American-Essentials/dp/0393921107 |title=Purchase We the People: An Introduction to American Politics (Ninth Essentials Edition) |publisher=Amazon |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> This textbook, which she coauthored with [[Benjamin Ginsberg (political scientist)|Benjamin Ginsberg]], [[Theodore J. Lowi]], [[Margaret Weir]], and (in later editions) Andrea L. Campbell, had been published in 12 editions by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wwnorton.com/books/9780393679670 |title=We the People |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nTolbert has also published dozens of articles in political science and public policy journals.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=N3evtQoAAAAJ&hl=en |title=Caroline J. Tolbert Google Scholar Profile |year=2020 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Her 2006 article with Karen Mossberger, \"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", was published in The ''[[Public Administration Review]]'', and was subsequently named by the journal as one of the 75 most influential articles ever published there since the journal's founding in 1940.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226011209/publicadministrationreview.org/full-list/ |title=PAR 75 Most Influential Articles |work=Public Administration Review |year=2014 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nTolbert was the solo recipient of the 2009-2011 Collegiate Scholar Award at the University of Iowa, which recognizes \"mid-career faculty for exceptional achievement\".<ref name=collegiate>{{cite web |url=https://clas.uiowa.edu/faculty/clas-collegiate-scholar-award |title=CLAS Collegiate Scholar Award |year=2019 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 citation analysis by the political scientists Hannah June Kim and [[Bernard Grofman]] listed Tolbert as one of the most cited political scientists working at an American university in 2 different categories: the top 40 most cited women scholars, and the top 25 most cited political scientists who earned their PhD between 1995 and 1999 (inclusive).<ref name=kim19/>\n\nTolbert's work has been cited in news outlets like ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/iowa-caucus-explained.html |title=Why the Iowa Caucuses Are So Important |first1=David |last1=Botti |first2=Sarah |last2=Kerr |work=The New York Times |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/1/31/21087017/iowa-democratic-caucus-primary-process |title=The Iowa caucuses are broken. Here\u2019s an idea to fix the primary process |work=Vox |date=4 February 2020 |first=Sean |last=Illing |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/buttigieg-distanced-himself-from-liberals-and-his-campaign-took-off-11576578602 |title= Buttigieg Distanced Himself From Liberals, and His Campaign Took Off |date=17 December 2019 |first1=Sabrina |last1=Siddiqui |first2=Chad |last2=Day |first3=John |last3=McCormick |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> particularly her work relating to the sequence of [[United States presidential primary]] election contests and her 2010 book '' Why Iowa? How Caucuses and Sequential Elections Improve the Presidential Nominating Process''.\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", ''Public Administration Review'' (2006)\n*''We the people: An introduction to American politics'' (from 9th edition, 2012 onwards)\n*''Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity'' (2013)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Collegiate Scholar Award, University of Iowa (2009)<ref name=collegiate/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authoritycontrol}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tolbert, Caroline J.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:Colorado College faculty]]\n[[Category:Kent State University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Caroline Tolbert\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Colorado College]]|[[Kent State University]]|[[University of Iowa]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[University of California, Santa Barbara]]|[[University of Colorado, Boulder]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Collegiate Scholar Award, University of Iowa}}\n}}\n'''Caroline Tolbert''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]]. She is a professor of political science at the [[University of Iowa]]. She studies [[elections]], [[voting]], and [[civic engagement]] in American politics. Much of her work deals with peoples' capacity to use internet technology, digital technology policy, and the relationship between technology use and social participation.\n\n==Early work and education==\nTolbert attended the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]], graduating with a BA in political science in 1989.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://clas.uiowa.edu/polisci/people/caroline-j-tolbert |title=\nCaroline J. Tolbert |publisher=University of Iowa |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> She then received an MA in [[public policy]] from the [[University of Colorado, Boulder]] in 1991,<ref name=profile/> followed by a PhD in political science from the same institution in 1996.<ref name=kim19>{{cite journal |title=The Political Science 400: With Citation Counts by Cohort, Gender, and Subfield |doi=10.1017/S1049096518001786 |date=April 2019 |last1=Kim |first1=Hannah June |last2=Grofman |first2=Bernard |journal=PS: Political Science & Politics |volume=52 |issue=2 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/C1EDBF7220760F01A5C4A685DB3B3F44/S1049096518001786a.pdf/political_science_400_with_citation_counts_by_cohort_gender_and_subfield.pdf |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 1997, Tolbert was an information technology specialist at [[Colorado College]], and then joined the political science faculty at [[Kent State University]] in 1997.<ref name=profile/> In 2006 she moved to the University of Iowa.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nTolbert has been a coauthor of 8 books.<ref name=profile/> In 2013 she coauthored the book ''Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity'' with Karen Mossberger and William W. Franko. The book develops a notion of \"digital citizenship\", which captures the extent to which individuals are capable of regularly and effectively using technology related to the internet.<ref name=lseblog>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2013/03/19/book-review-digital-cities-the-internet-and-the-geography-of-opportunity/ |title=Book Review: Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity by Karen Mossberger et al |date=19 March 2013 |publisher=London School of Economics |last=Spicer |first=Zachary |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The authors focus on inequality in peoples' capacities to use internet technologies; Zachary Spicer, in a review of the book, wrote that they demonstrate that \"America is falling short in these areas and, as a result, information inequities are developing that could have deep and lasting impacts on the social fabric of the country.\"<ref name=lseblog/> The book also presents policy suggestions for making digital citizenship more equal.<ref name=lseblog/>\n\nTolbert became a coauthor of the American politics textbook ''We the people: An introduction to American politics'' when the book was in its ninth edition in 2012.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/We-People-Introduction-American-Essentials/dp/0393921107 |title=Purchase We the People: An Introduction to American Politics (Ninth Essentials Edition) |publisher=Amazon |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> This textbook, which she coauthored with [[Benjamin Ginsberg (political scientist)|Benjamin Ginsberg]], [[Theodore J. Lowi]], [[Margaret Weir]], and (in later editions) Andrea L. Campbell, had been published in 12 editions by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wwnorton.com/books/9780393679670 |title=We the People |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nTolbert has also published dozens of articles in political science and public policy journals.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=N3evtQoAAAAJ&hl=en |title=Caroline J. Tolbert Google Scholar Profile |year=2020 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Her 2006 article with Karen Mossberger, \"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", was published in The ''[[Public Administration Review]]'', and was subsequently named by the journal as one of the 75 most influential articles ever published there since the journal's founding in 1940.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226011209/publicadministrationreview.org/full-list/ |title=PAR 75 Most Influential Articles |work=Public Administration Review |year=2014 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nTolbert was the solo recipient of the 2009-2011 Collegiate Scholar Award at the University of Iowa, which recognizes \"mid-career faculty for exceptional achievement\".<ref name=collegiate>{{cite web |url=https://clas.uiowa.edu/faculty/clas-collegiate-scholar-award |title=CLAS Collegiate Scholar Award |year=2019 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 citation analysis by the political scientists Hannah June Kim and [[Bernard Grofman]] listed Tolbert as one of the most cited political scientists working at an American university in 2 different categories: the top 40 most cited women scholars, and the top 25 most cited political scientists who earned their PhD between 1995 and 1999 (inclusive).<ref name=kim19/>\n\nTolbert's work has been cited in news outlets like ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/iowa-caucus-explained.html |title=Why the Iowa Caucuses Are So Important |first1=David |last1=Botti |first2=Sarah |last2=Kerr |work=The New York Times |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/1/31/21087017/iowa-democratic-caucus-primary-process |title=The Iowa caucuses are broken. Here\u2019s an idea to fix the primary process |work=Vox |date=4 February 2020 |first=Sean |last=Illing |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/buttigieg-distanced-himself-from-liberals-and-his-campaign-took-off-11576578602 |title= Buttigieg Distanced Himself From Liberals, and His Campaign Took Off |date=17 December 2019 |first1=Sabrina |last1=Siddiqui |first2=Chad |last2=Day |first3=John |last3=McCormick |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> particularly her work relating to the sequence of [[United States presidential primary]] election contests and her 2010 book '' Why Iowa? How Caucuses and Sequential Elections Improve the Presidential Nominating Process''.\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"The Effects of E-Government on Trust and Confidence in Government\", ''Public Administration Review'' (2006)\n*''We the people: An introduction to American politics'' (from 9th edition, 2012 onwards)\n*''Digital Cities: The Internet and the Geography of Opportunity'' (2013)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Collegiate Scholar Award, University of Iowa (2009)<ref name=collegiate/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authoritycontrol}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tolbert, Caroline J.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:Colorado College faculty]]\n[[Category:Kent State University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "+link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caroline_Tolbert"}
